liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: More than 1,200 bank branches have shut down in the past six years – with more expected until 2026 – as the nation’s banks slowly phase out Australian consumers’ access to cash. Regional communities have been disproportionately affected by these branch closures. The bosses of major banks will be questioned in a Senate inquiry about the future of regional banking. The Senate will be hearing from representatives form Commonwealth Bank, Westpac and NAB this morning followed by ANZ this afternoon.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A new human rights report says that women strip searched in Queensland prisons were left without dignity and felt humiliated, while the practice didn't make prisons safer. The Queensland Human Rights Commission has released findings from its review into the issue, calling for an end to the practice. Interviews with prisoners and staff at all five of Queensland's women's prisons were conducted as part of the review. "You are stripped of everything. They don't just strip your clothes; they strip away your dignity," one prisoner told the review. It found that strip searches very rarely found any hidden contraband, and suggested the practice be replaced by body scanning technology. You can read the rest of the story below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Strip searching women in prisons 'dehumanising', report finds
